Description
"Jolly" Joe Cappabianco has been leaving a mark for 30 years in the tattoo community and we want to celebrate that! Join us of Sunday, February 19th from 4:00 - 8:00 for a night to gather, eat, drink and talk a lot of shit!

What you should expect:

Cocktail Party, Whiskey Tasting, Noshes and Celebration

Food will be curated by Chef Mark Bestmann

Cash Bar - Perfectly Curated Cocktail Menu based around everything that makes Joe Happy. Just kidding - that would be a really small cocktail menu. The menu will make us happy which will probably make Joe not so Jolly, which also makes us happy.

"Jolly" Joe's Private Single Barrel of Bourbon to taste and purchase.

Guest Bartender @jimelitwalk - You may not get what you order, but you will get what you need!

Joe will also be handing out raffle tickets (no extra charge), for chances to win Tattoo time with him, posters, prints, books, and much more. 
  So don’t miss what will hopefully be a very memorable event! Find the link in my Linktree in my bio.

👇👇PLEASE READ👇👇. Hey all. 
So I’m happy to announce that my Back Bone barrel pick has arrived and will
Be available for a free tasting, as well as purchase. This Sunday February 19th at Ordinary, down town New Haven.
 Now if you’ve purchased a ticket for my 30+ tattoo anniversary, then the tasting and party will take place from 4-8. 
  If you didn’t purchase a ticket for the day. I invite you to come by Ordinary from 7-8pm. Free samples will be offered, and whisky can be purchased on site. 
  Ordinary will also have a cash bar with special cocktails to help me celebrate! 
  Please be aware that we will have a hard out at Ordinary at 8pm, as we will be headed over to the Owl shop (right round the corner), from 8 on. 
  So hope ta see ya there.

We had an incredible time at this years Capobianco family picnic, out on LI. Need to thank my cousin @gails.cucina and her mom(my aunt Connie), for keeping this going. Every year goes by, and things change. Especially this late in all our lives. Not too sound too sappy. But Hell, time is to short, and we all need to spend our time wisely, to be with the ones we love. Something I’m learning all to quickly that I’ve lost so much with family and friends. But enough of that. It was a tremendously wonderful afternoon, and I can’t wait for all of us to get back together again! Thanks for @bearssmokehouse for helping my Aunts, and Uncles out with some of the food service. Everyone loved the bbq! @neptunemike for crushing it at the bar😁! Till next time!

In the late summer of 2003, Eric Merril, Julio Rodriguez, and I opened Hope Gallery, in down town New Haven. In the first year, we invited Tim Harris to join us, and shortly after that, Phil Young. 
  We had 6 great years in that location, on Chapel street. But I felt the need to get out of the downtown area, and do something a bit different. 
  This year marks Hope Galleries 20th year of business. The core group of artists has remained the same, minus Julio who went on to Open “Tattoolios” in Wallingford CT. Since than we’ve been blessed with artists, Christian Perez, Shane Baker, Adam Harmon, and Joe Santiago. 
  So I’d like to invite you all to help celebrate our 20 years of doing tattoos, art, and other unique events at the studio. We’ll be hosting a party, featuring art from all the fellers. As well as work from guests we’ve hosted over the years. 
  We’ll also have special features from down towns amazing cocktail bar, Ordinary. As well as CTs New England Brewing co. Bears Smokehouse will have their fantastic bbq food truck. 
  There will be limited t-shirts, stickers, prints, and, more for sale and giveaway. Raffles and all other sorts of stuff. 
  Hope to see you at Hope, Saturday October 7th at 3pm!

  Sincerely 
Joe Capobianco. 

835 Woodward Ave
New Haven, CT 06512

Taking the time to revisit tattoos created a decade or more ago isn’t just a trip down memory lane – it’s a crucial aspect of artistic growth. Examining healed work from the past provides a unique perspective, offering insights into how our art ages and evolves over time.⁣
⁣
By studying these tattoos, we gain a deeper understanding of what stands the test of time and what might need refinement. It’s a humbling process that allows us to learn from our own work, identify strengths, and pinpoint areas for improvement.⁣
⁣
Embracing this reflective practice isn’t about dwelling on past mistakes but rather acknowledging the continuous journey of improvement. It’s a powerful tool for honing our skills, fostering creativity, and ensuring that each piece we create carries the wisdom of experience.⁣
⁣
⁣
#howtotattoo #healedtattoos #tattootalk #tattoopodcast ⁣

I started tattooing back in 1992/3. A time before social media and the internet. Magazines, conventions, and the word of mouth of other tattooers was how one found influences. I was fortunate enough to start in a shop surrounded by other artists that had a hunger to learn more, and fast. My first “rising star” tattooer I’d met was @paulbooth And I will say, it changed the way I thought about tattooing, right outta the gate. Over the next several years I was introduced to the art, and work of tattooers like @eddydeutsche @cainforge @timothyhoyer @guyaitchisonart @j_rudy_gtc @bernieluther @mariobarthtattoo Chris Trevino, Marcus Pacheco, @marty_holcomb @judyparkerstattoos Cap Szumski, @& of course one of the biggest influences back in the day @filipleu This is probably the short list. Because back then every day that you grabbed a magazine, purchased flash, traveled to another city, hit a convention, or was lucky enough to leave the country. The amount of new tattooers, and new styles, and personalities was incredible. And to myself, a young up and coming tattooer, just wanting to learn, and glean new experiences, and gain new friends. Hell it was an amazing time to start. Well, if ya made it to the end. I hope I didn’t bore ya too much. Enjoy the day…🥃
Tattooer, World traveler, eater of good foods, and drinker of fine whiskeys.
